urlDecode.!doc:
This API enables the app developer decode the string.

Example #1
<pre>
  var result = kony.net.urlDecode(“hello*_%40+world”);
  kony.print(result);
</pre>

The output will be “hello*_@ world”

@param {String} queryParams – Mandatory, The queryParams is the string which needs to be decoded.
@param {String} ExemptionString - Optional, String containing all the characters that are to be exempted from decoding. This parameter is only specific to iOS Platform. Android & Windows platforms will ignore it. But iOS respect the characters and decode accordingly.
@Available on Android, iOS, Windows 10

urlEncode.!doc:
This API enables the app developer encode the string.
It translates the given string into application/x-www-form-urlencoded format using a UTF-8 encoding scheme.

When encoding a string, the following rules apply:
  The alphanumeric characters "a" through "z", "A" through "Z" and "0" through "9" remain the same.
  The special characters ".", "-", "*", and "_" remain the same.
  The space character "" is converted into a plus sign "+".
  All other characters are unsafe and are first converted into one or more bytes using some encoding scheme. Then each byte is represented by the 3-character string "%xy", wherexyis the two-digit hexadecimal representation of the byte.
  All the rules applied in reverse while decoding. After decoding the encoded string original string will be return.

For example using UTF-8 as the encoding scheme the string "The string üfoo-bar" would get converted to "The+string+%C3%BCfoo-bar" because in UTF-8 the character ü is encoded as two bytes C3 (hex) and BC (hex).

  Example #1
  <pre>
    var result = kony.net.urlEncode(“hello*_ world”);
    kony.print(result);
  </pre>

  The output will be “hello*_+world”

  Example #2
  <pre>
    var exemptionString =  "helloworl-*_.";
    var result = kony.net.urlEncode(“hello*_ world”, exemptionString);
    kony.print(result);
  </pre>

    IOS output: will be “hello*_+worl%64”
    Android and Windows output: will be “hello*_+world”

@param {String} queryParams – Mandatory, The queryParams is the string which needs to be encoded.
@param {String} ExemptionString - Optional, String containing all the characters that are to be exempted from encoding This parameter is only specific to iOS Platform. Android & Windows platforms will ignore it. But iOS respect the characters and encode accordingly.
@Available on Android, iOS, Windows 10

